land":"Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Strathern, Leicestershire, England":"Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Tattershall, Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England":"Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Tattershall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Tattersall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tattersall","meanings":["English (Lancashire and west Yorkshire): habitational name from Tattershall in Lincolnshire, named from the Old English personal name <i>Tāthere</i> (genitive <i>Tātheres</i>) + Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":17,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":26,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Tattershall was born about 1198, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Walter de Tattershall, was 30 and his mother, Iseult Pantulf, was 29. He had at least 1 son with Matilda d'Aubigny. He died on 16 July 1249, in Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 52."},"et":{"Abt 1198–16 July 1249":"umbes 1198–16. juuli 1249","1198–1249":"1198–1249","1197–1240":"1197–1240","1222–1273":"1222–1273","1170–1199":"1170–1199","1170–1222":"1170–1222","16 July 1249":"16. juuli 1249","Aft 1222":"pärast 1222","1198":"1198","1197":"1197","1273":"1273","1240":"1240","1170":"1170","Abt 1240":"umbes 1240","1249":"1249","1215":"1215","about 5 December 1222":"umbes 5. detsember 1222","1224":"1224","1222":"1222","Abt 11